{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17502672","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17502672"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:48:23+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:48:23+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1888"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1888","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1888"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.23,0.29,0.12,0.15,0.2]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1888"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108181"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1888","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1888"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1888"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90593"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"272"},{"type":"tags","id":"1155"},{"type":"tags","id":"6238"},{"type":"tags","id":"9600"},{"type":"tags","id":"11606"},{"type":"tags","id":"12917"},{"type":"tags","id":"12919"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2506"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3751"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40359"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108181","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/108181"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 69-year-old man is brought into the Emergency Department by ambulance from the scene of a motor vehicle crash. Upon arrival, the team has performed a primary survey with necessary interventions. An endotracheal tube was inserted due to a Glasgow Coma Scale of 7 and the patient is otherwise stable. One of the nurses becomes concerned about the patient\u0027s face, temporarily stops medications and asks for an urgent review. As the duty intern starts to undertake their review of the patient they notice crepitus on palpation of the patient\u0027s eyelids, forehead and neck. A photograph of the patient is shown (Image).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely explanation for the physical sign visible in the photograph?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Pneumothorax","Fracture to the base of skull","Fractured nose","Cuff leak on the endotracheal tube","Anaphylactic reaction to a drug"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has gross periorbital swelling and crepitus noted on palpation of the face. This is most likely to be air in the subcutaneous tissues tracking from a \u003Cstrong\u003Epneumothorax.\u003C/strong\u003E The crepitus that is felt on palpation is termed subcutaneous emphysema. Whilst air travelling up so far in the subcutaneous tissues would not be a common feature of a pneumothorax, subcutaneous emphysema can often be felt in the neck, and so extension up to eyelids is not unknown. Even a small pneumothorax can produce this clinical picture and can easily be missed in these circumstances. In this patient observing this finding should prompt the clinician to continue their assessment with a focus on vital signs (respiratory rate, SpO2, blood pressure) and assessment of the thorax - including auscultation findings, percussion for hyper-resonance, and tracheal deviation. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EA fracture to the base of skull\u003C/strong\u003E may cause subcutaneous emphysema, but it would be very unlikely to be as extensive as present in this patient. The patient does not have other classic signs of a base of skull fracture including periorbital haematoma (\u0022raccoon eyes\u0022) or CSF rhinorrhoea.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EA fractured nose\u003C/strong\u003E will not cause subcutaneous emphysema.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EA cuff leak on endotracheal tube\u003C/strong\u003E can occur when the cuff of the tube is damaged on the teeth during insertion. This can be detected by an audible gurgling on expiration and bubbling above the tube. It does not cause subcutaneous emphysema.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAnaphylactic reaction to a drug\u003C/strong\u003E is a possible cause of facial swelling and should be considered as a differential but will not cause subcutaneous emphysema.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Subcutaneous emphysema in the face and neck following trauma is most commonly associated with pneumothorax.","Crepitus on palpation is the hallmark physical finding of subcutaneous emphysema.","Extensive facial subcutaneous emphysema should prompt thorough assessment of the respiratory system including auscultation, percussion, and evaluation for tracheal deviation."],"references":["Aghajanzadeh M, Dehnadi A, Ebrahimi H, et al. Classification and Management of Subcutaneous Emphysema: a 10-Year Experience. Indian J Surg. 2015;77(Suppl 2):673-677. doi:10.1007/s12262-013-0975-4"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90593"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1888"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"19447"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"19447","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/19447"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/ee062322-06b5-421c-94c6-63915768c849.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/ee062322-06b5-421c-94c6-63915768c849.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":800,"height":600}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90593","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/90593"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-08T08:14:12+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-08T08:16:18+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1888"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108181"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"11","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec1","name":"Respiratory Medicine","synonyms":["Pulmonology"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"65","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/65"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Investigations","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"c